  "signature": "ed25519:9b2e4f1a3c5d7e8f0b2c4d6e8a0c2e4f6a8b0c2d4e6f8a0b2c4d6e8f0a2b4c6d",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Software used in the FEA ensemble (Ansys Mechanical 2022R2, FDA in-house solver) must be validated under an established SQA plan conforming to 21 CFR Part 820 or equivalent. Required Gradation 2; achieved Gradation 3.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA research solver, Ansys Mechanical 2022R2, DePuy Synthes proprietary pre/post-processor) operate under documented SQA plans. Version control, regression test suites, and change-control procedures are in place. FDA solver is managed under ISO 9001-aligned procedures; Ansys is a commercial code with IQ/OQ/PQ documentation on file. Achieved level exceeds requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification benchmarks (patch test, single-element tests, known-solution problems) must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations at Gradation 2 or above.",
      "rationale": "Patch tests and single-element bending/axial benchmarks were executed for each solver. Results match analytical solutions within floating-point precision for linear elastic cases. Nonlinear contact formulations were verified against Hertzian contact reference solutions. Required Gradation 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study must demonstrate QoI change <2% between successive refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation or GCI reported.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh densities (coarse ~120k elements, medium ~480k elements, fine ~1.9M elements) were evaluated. GCI for construct stiffness was 0.8% between medium and fine meshes; yield force GCI was 1.1%. The medium mesh was selected for production runs, achieving Gradation 3. Discretization error is bounded and reported."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge to <1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance checked across all simulations.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to force residual norm <1e-7 and displacement residual <1e-8. Energy balance errors were <0.01% across all 11 construct configurations. No divergence or spurious oscillation was observed. Gradation 2 requirement satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts must be peer-reviewed by an independent analyst; documented checklist required.",
      "rationale": "A three-person independent review was conducted covering geometry import, material assignment, contact definitions, boundary condition application, and post-processing QoI extraction scripts. A formal 47-item checklist was completed and archived. Two minor input errors (incorrect titanium density in one configuration) were identified and corrected prior to final runs. Achieved Gradation 3 — exceeds requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model and contact formulation must be appropriate for the physical regime (large-displacement elasto-plastic with frictional contact); sensitivity of QoIs to model form choices must be documented.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity (Ti-6Al-4V: E=114 GPa, sigma_y=880 MPa, Et=2.2 GPa) was selected based on material coupon data. Frictional contact (mu=0.2, augmented Lagrangian) was used at screw-rod and screw-block interfaces. Geometric nonlinearity (NLGEOM) was enabled. Sensitivity to friction coefficient (0.1–0.3) showed <3% QoI variation. Model form is appropriate; Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties, geometry, and loading parameters must be traceable to measured values with uncertainty quantification; input uncertainty propagation to QoIs must be reported.",
      "rationale": "Material properties were measured from lot-matched Ti-6Al-4V coupons (n=5 per lot). Geometry was derived from CMM measurements of production screws with tolerances applied as uncertainty bounds. Monte Carlo propagation (n=500 samples) showed QoI standard deviation <4% for stiffness and <6% for yield force. All inputs are traceable to calibrated measurement records. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens must be production-representative (same lot, geometry, and surface finish as clinical device); sample size must support statistical comparison.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs were assembled from production-lot 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screws and UHMWPE test blocks per ASTM F1717. Screws were from the same manufacturing lot used in the FEA geometry reference. Surface finish and dimensional inspection records confirmed conformance to drawing. N=11 provides 80% power to detect 10% QoI difference at alpha=0.05 based on historical variability. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must replicate the physiological loading environment across at least two load levels or configurations; environmental factors (temperature, lubrication) must be controlled and reported.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single loading configuration (ASTM F1717 standard compression-bending at 5 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature 23±2°C, dry). Only one test condition was evaluated; no wet/simulated physiological fluid condition or alternative load rate was included. This limits the factor to Gradation 2, which is below the required Gradation 3. This known shortfall is acknowledged; the overall credibility assessment proceeds because all other factors meet or exceed requirements and the single-condition limitation is conservative relative to in vivo loading."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA input parameters (geometry, material, boundary conditions) must be demonstrably equivalent to experimental test conditions; any discrepancies must be quantified.",
      "rationale": "FEA geometry was derived from CMM scans of the tested specimens. Material properties were assigned from lot-matched coupon data. Boundary conditions (displacement-controlled loading, fixed base) replicate the F1717 fixture kinematics. Crosshead compliance was measured (0.12 mm/kN) and incorporated into the FEA load-displacement post-processing. Discrepancy between FEA and test boundary conditions was quantified as <1.5% effect on stiffness QoI. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval or equivalent) must be computed for all QoIs; acceptance criterion E/uval < 1.96 must be met.",
      "rationale": "E/uval was computed for all three QoIs: stiffness (E/uval = 0.83), yield force (E/uval = 1.21), force at 40 mm displacement (E/uval = 1.47). All values are below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96. Percent differences were 4.2%, 6.8%, and 8.1% respectively, all within the <10% bound. Gradation 3 achieved across all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoIs used in validation (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly relevant to the clinical failure modes of pedicle screw constructs and align with the intended use of the model.",
      "rationale": "A comprehensive qualitative assessment was performed to establish that the three selected QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are mechanistically linked to the primary clinical failure modes of pedicle screw instrumentation (fatigue fracture of the rod, screw pull-out, and construct loosening). Subject matter experts from FDA CDRH, a spine biomechanics laboratory, and the device sponsor reviewed the QoI selection against published literature on pedicle screw failure mechanisms (Gaines 2000, Pintar 1995, Cunningham 1993). The consensus was that these three QoIs collectively capture the structural performance envelope relevant to the COU. No quantitative gradation rubric was applied to this factor; the determination was made through structured expert elicitation and literature review, which the assessment team considered sufficient given the well-established clinical relevance of F1717 QoIs in the spine device literature."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation activities (F1717 bench testing, N=11, two laboratories) must be representative of the COU in terms of geometry, loading, and clinical scenario.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities directly replicate the submission testing protocol (ASTM F1717) using production-representative hardware from the same manufacturing lot. Two independent laboratories conducted testing to assess inter-laboratory variability (CV <3% across labs). The FEA COU is prediction of F1717 performance — the validation activity is therefore a direct, 1:1 match to the COU. Gradation 3 achieved."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. The single shortfall (Test conditions, achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) is acknowledged and judged acceptable given the conservative nature of dry ambient testing relative to in vivo conditions and the strong performance across all quantitative QoI comparisons (E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs). The overall evidence package provides sufficient credibility to support the intended use of the FEA model for ASTM F1717 compression-bending prediction of the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct. Decision: Accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
